# Cursor Rules for Purposemed.ai Training Documentation

## Project Context

Docusaurus 3.8.1 site for PurposeMed executive AI training. 25 pages covering prompting, context management, research, automation, governance, and leadership. Dark-mode only. Deployed to GitHub Pages at `https://ximxim.github.io/WorkflowyOS-Docs/`.

Brand: "Purposemed.ai" in UI, "Workflowy.ai" in footer attribution only.

PurposeMed context: Cross-border telehealth with three service lines — Freddie (HIV/PrEP), Frida (ADHD), Foria (gender-affirming care). Always reference these in healthcare examples.

## General Markdown Preferences

- **ALWAYS prefer markdown syntax over HTML elements** when the same result can be achieved
- Use markdown headers (`#`, `##`, `###`) instead of HTML `<h1>`, `<h2>`, `<h3>` tags
- Use markdown images (`![alt text](image-url)`) instead of `<img>` tags when possible
- Use markdown emphasis (`**bold**`, `*italic*`) instead of `<strong>` and `<em>` tags
- Use markdown lists (`-`, `1.`) instead of `<ul>`/`<ol>` with `<li>` tags
- Use markdown links (`[text](url)`) instead of `<a>` tags
- Use markdown code blocks (``` or `) instead of `<code>` tags
- Use markdown blockquotes (`>`) instead of `<blockquote>` tags
- Use horizontal lines (`---`) instead of `<hr>` tags

## Docusaurus-Specific Guidelines

- For documentation files in the `docs/` directory, prioritize clean markdown
- Use MDX components (React) only when markdown cannot achieve the desired result
- For complex layouts requiring CSS classes, document the reason and consider if a simpler markdown alternative exists
- When using HTML elements, add a comment explaining why markdown is insufficient
- Use markdown frontmatter for metadata (sidebar_position, title, etc.)
- Use Docusaurus admonitions: `:::note`, `:::tip`, `:::warning`, `:::danger`, `:::info`

## Mermaid Diagrams

The site uses Mermaid diagrams extensively (39 diagrams across 24 pages).

- Use ` ```mermaid ` code fences in markdown files
- **Quote all node labels** with special characters: `A["Label with (parens)"]`
- Never use bare parentheses in labels — Mermaid interprets them as node shapes
- Keep diagrams concise: 5–15 nodes max
- Preferred types: `flowchart TD/LR`, `timeline`, `sequenceDiagram`, `mindmap`, `quadrantChart`
- Always run `npm run build` after editing diagrams to verify syntax

## Custom Components

- **FAQStructuredData**: Prop is `faqs` (NOT `items`). Array of `{question, answer}`.
- **Card / CardHeader / CardBody**: For grid layouts (see `welcome.mdx`)
- **Button**: CTA buttons in MDX pages

## Sidebar Structure

Uses HTML headings + flat `autogenerated` items. Do NOT wrap in a `category` when it would be the only child — creates redundant nesting.

## Content Structure

- Use descriptive headings that form a clear hierarchy
- Separate major sections with horizontal lines (`---`)
- Keep paragraphs concise and focused
- Training/curriculum tone, second-person voice addressing executives
- Healthcare examples grounded in PurposeMed context (Freddie/Frida/Foria)

## File Organization

- Place images in `static/img/` directory
- Use relative paths for internal links
- Name files using kebab-case (lowercase with hyphens)
- Logo: `static/img/logo.svg` (PurposeMed icon), Favicon: `static/img/favicon.svg`

## Critical Rules

- `onBrokenLinks: 'throw'` — build fails on broken internal links. Always verify links.
- All `@docusaurus/*` packages must match core version (3.8.1). Never install mismatched versions.
- Autogenerated category indexes are NOT direct routes — link to specific pages, not category paths.
- Always run `npm run build` before committing to catch broken links and diagram syntax errors.

## When HTML is Acceptable

- Complex responsive layouts that require CSS Grid or Flexbox
- Interactive components that need JavaScript functionality
- Custom styling that cannot be achieved with markdown
- Docusaurus-specific components that enhance functionality
